<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF99FFE5FE5D1E818779B6AC" authorityName="Rogers &amp; Cruz-Rivera" authorityYear="2021" box="[452,557,1164,1191]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hyalellidae" genus="Hyalella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="14" pageNumber="813" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF99FFE5FE5D1E818779B6AC" bold="true" box="[452,557,1164,1191]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="813">Hyalella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
‘ 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF99FFE5FDAD1E8187D3B6AC" authority="(Saussure, 1858)" baseAuthorityName="Saussure" baseAuthorityYear="1858" box="[564,647,1164,1191]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hyalellidae" genus="Hyalella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="14" pageNumber="813" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="azteca">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF99FFE5FDAD1E8187D3B6AC" bold="true" box="[564,647,1164,1191]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="813">azteca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’
</emphasis>
(Saussure, 1858)
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E8403669FF99FFE5FF591ECF85A7B7A0" blockId="14.[160,1156,1218,1451]" pageId="14" pageNumber="813">
This taxon seems to be a species complex that is widespread in North America. It was originally collected from a cistern in 
<collectingCountry id="90E876F9FF99FFE5FDD11EE987CCB6F6" box="[584,664,1252,1277]" name="Mexico" pageId="14" pageNumber="813">Mexico</collectingCountry>
and reported from 
<collectingCountry id="90E876F9FF99FFE5FCE61EE98156B6F6" box="[895,1026,1252,1277]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="14" pageNumber="813">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
as early as 1933 (
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF99FFE5FF711F0A84FEB72B" author="Shoemaker CR" box="[232,426,1287,1312]" pageId="14" pageNumber="813" pagination="1 - 24" refId="ref29903" refString="Shoemaker CR. 1933. Amphipoda from Florida and the West Indies. Am Mus Novit. 598: 1 - 24." type="journal article" year="1933">Shoemaker 1933</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF99FFE5FE221F0A84A6B72B" author="Shoemaker CR" box="[443,498,1287,1312]" pageId="14" pageNumber="813" pagination="230 - 253" refId="ref29926" refString="Shoemaker CR. 1935. The amphipods of Porto Rico and the Virgin Islands. Sci Surv Porto Rico Virgin Islands. 14: 230 - 253." type="journal article" year="1935">1935</bibRefCitation>
). We collected material, identified using Baldinger’s key (2004), in St. Thomas from Turpentine Run ghut, Cats and Chickens ghut, the impoundments on Mahogany Run ghut, and from Dorothea turtle pond. We expect that 
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF99FFE5FB8C1F418172B76E" box="[1045,1062,1356,1381]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="813">H</emphasis>
. ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF99FFE5FBAE1F41812AB76E" baseAuthorityName="Saussure" baseAuthorityYear="1858" box="[1079,1150,1356,1381]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hyalellidae" genus="Hyalella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="14" pageNumber="813" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="azteca">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF99FFE5FBAE1F41812AB76E" box="[1079,1150,1356,1381]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="813">azteca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ was introduced with ornamental aquatic plants. This is the first record from the 
<collectingCountry id="90E876F9FF99FFE5FBD81F6285BBB7A0" name="Virgin Islands" pageId="14" pageNumber="813">Virgin Islands</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
